        "phase": "Predict Phase",
        "learnerExperience": "Students read a short printed account (or listen to the teacher narrate) the story of Mwangi, a 45-year-old maize farmer from Kericho, who collapses while carrying a heavy sack of harvested maize uphill to his storage shed. They are shown a side-by-side diagram: a healthy coronary artery versus one that is 70% blocked by fatty deposits. Before any instruction, students individually write responses to three prompt questions in their notebooks: (1) What do you think happened inside Mwangi's body when the artery became blocked? (2) Why do you think his lips turned blue? (3) Why would carrying a heavy load make his heart work harder? Students then share predictions with a shoulder partner for 90 seconds before a few are shared whole-class.",
        "teacherMoves": "Display the scenario and diagram on the board or print copies. Say verbatim: 'Before we learn anything new, I want to know what YOU think is happening to Mwangi. There are no wrong answers right now — we are scientists making our best guess with what we know.' Allow 3 minutes of silent individual writing. Then say: 'Turn to your neighbour and share your three predictions. You have 90 seconds — go.' After partner talk, cold-call 3 students using name cards: 'Achieng, what did you and your partner predict about the blue lips?' Apply 10-second WAIT TIME after each response before probing. Do not correct predictions — instead say: 'Interesting — let's keep that idea and see if our investigation today gives us evidence to confirm or revise it.' Write 2-3 student predictions verbatim on the board under the heading 'OUR PREDICTIONS — Day 1'.",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Elicitation of Prior Knowledge: By surfacing predictions before instruction, the teacher gains a diagnostic window into student mental models and misconceptions. Writing predictions creates a public record that can be revisited and revised — reinforcing the scientific practice of developing and revising explanations based on evidence (NGSS SEP 6). Connecting predictions to a real Kenyan farmer makes the phenomenon personally relevant and emotionally engaging.",
