        "teacherMoves": "After gallery walk (allow 3 minutes), say: 'I noticed several groups used the phrase that cells in the middle need a delivery system. Scientists call that delivery system the circulatory system. Write that in your notes right now.' Pause 30 seconds for writing. Then cold-call 3 students from different groups: 'Kamau — your group said diffusion is too slow for large organisms. How does that connect back to Mwangi's heart attack?' WAIT 12 seconds. If no response, prompt: 'Think about what the coronary artery was blocked — what could no longer get through to the heart muscle cells?' After student response, validate and extend: 'Exactly — the heart muscle cells are multicellular tissue far from any oxygen source except the blood. When the coronary artery is blocked, those cells face the same problem as the centre of our big cube — no delivery, no survival.' Write on board: 'Blocked artery → cells starved of O₂ and glucose → heart muscle fails → whole-body pump fails → all cells affected.' Ask students to copy this chain into notebooks.",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Constructing Explanations (NGSS SEP 6) combined with Evidence-to-Phenomenon Linking: Students do not simply define the circulatory system — they derive the need for it from their own evidence, then immediately apply that reasoning back to the anchoring phenomenon. The teacher's explicit chain-of-causality written on the board models scientific reasoning and gives students a scaffold for constructing their own explanations. Gallery walk ensures peer-to-peer learning and validates diverse ways of expressing the same concept.",
