        "learnerExperience": "Each student receives 2 sticky notes and writes one question per note — questions that the Kericho farmer's story has raised that they do not yet know how to answer. Examples may include: 'What exactly is inside blood that carries oxygen?', 'How does the heart pump blood?', 'What are fatty deposits and why do they block arteries?', 'Why does exercise make your heart beat faster?', 'How do doctors fix a blocked coronary artery?' Students post their sticky notes on a dedicated section of the classroom wall labelled 'OUR DRIVING QUESTION BOARD — Transport in Animals.' The teacher, with student help, reads the questions aloud and clusters them into 4-5 thematic groups (e.g., HEART STRUCTURE, BLOOD VESSELS, BLOOD COMPOSITION, WHY WE NEED TRANSPORT, DISEASES AND TREATMENT). The class agrees on the overarching Driving Question written at the top: 'Why did the Kericho farmer's heart attack affect his whole body — and how does the circulatory system keep every cell in your body alive?'",
        "teacherMoves": "Distribute two sticky notes per student. Say: 'Write one genuine question per sticky note — something you truly do not yet understand about Mwangi's situation or the circulatory system. These will guide our learning for the whole unit.' Allow 3 minutes of silent writing. Then say: 'Come up and post your questions on the board.' As students post, begin reading them aloud and ask: 'Who else had a similar question?' Group related questions together physically on the board. Say: 'I notice several of you asked about what carries oxygen in blood — that question will be answered in Lesson 3. I notice others asked why the heart beats faster during heavy work — we will investigate that in Lesson 2.' Write lesson numbers next to each cluster so students see the roadmap. Cold-call 2 students: 'Wanjiru, can you read your question to the class? Why did that question come to you?' WAIT 10 seconds. Photograph the DQB or instruct the class monitor to preserve it. End with: 'Every time we learn something new, we will come back here and mark off questions we can now answer. This board belongs to YOU.'",
