        "teacherMoves": "Say: 'Scientists always start with a model — a drawing that captures what they currently understand, even if it is incomplete. I want you to build your Day 1 model right now. It does not have to be perfect — it has to be honest about what you understand TODAY.' Display the two-column prompt on the board: 'Left side: small organism + diffusion. Right side: large organism + the transport problem.' Circulate for 5 minutes while students draw. Look at 4-5 notebooks and offer specific praise: 'I like that you labelled the diffusion distance — that shows you understand the SA:V argument.' After 5 minutes, say: 'Hold up your notebook. Look at your neighbour's model. What has your neighbour included that you might want to add?' Allow 60 seconds of peer comparison. Then say: 'Put today's date on your model. We will come back to it in every lesson and add new layers. By Lesson 6, your model will look very different — and much more complete.' Cold-call 1 student: 'Otieno, show us your model and explain one thing it shows about why Mwangi needed his coronary artery to be clear.' WAIT 12 seconds.",
