        "learnerExperience": "Learners retrieve their cumulative annotated circulatory system model, which has been revised across all eight lessons. They spend 5 minutes making final additions — specifically adding: (1) labels for coronary arteries and their role in supplying the heart muscle; (2) annotations showing how atherosclerotic plaque narrows the coronary artery; (3) arrows showing how reduced cardiac output cascades to affect peripheral tissues, with a note explaining the blue lips; and (4) a small Kenyan lifestyle risk-factor key in the corner (symbols for nyama choma, smoking, inactivity, excess salt). Groups then conduct a 2-minute gallery walk in which they place their final model next to their Lesson 1 initial sketch and stand beside it. Two groups share a brief (90-second) verbal presentation: 'Here is what our model showed in Lesson 1. Here is what it shows now. The biggest change is _____ because _____.' The class responds with one 'warm' comment and one 'wonder' question per presenting group. Learners end by completing a 3-2-1 exit reflection in their books.",
        "teacherMoves": "Say: 'Your model has been growing for eight lessons. This is its final form. You have 5 minutes to add these four final elements — I am putting them on the board.' Write the four required additions on the board clearly. Set a visible 5-minute timer. Circulate and prompt: 'I see your coronary artery label — now add the arrow showing what happens when it is blocked.' 'Your risk-factor key is good — can you add one specific Kenyan food or habit next to each symbol?' After 5 minutes, say: 'Gallery walk — place your final model next to your Lesson 1 sketch. Stand with your model.' Allow 2 minutes of silent gallery walking so learners can observe other groups' models. Then select 2 groups to present: choose one group whose model shows strong conceptual growth and one group whose model has a particularly clear representation of the disease cascade. Give each group exactly 90 seconds. After each presentation, say to the class: 'One warm comment — something specific you appreciated. One wonder — a question this model makes you want to ask.' Cold-call 2 responses (one warm, one wonder) per presenting group. After presentations, say: 'Final task — in your books, complete this 3-2-1: Three things you now understand about the circulatory system. Two things you would change about the Kericho farmer's lifestyle to protect his heart. One question you still have.' Allow 3 minutes. WAIT TIME: Do not prompt or help during these 3 minutes. Collect 3-2-1 slips or photograph book pages as a summative formative record.",
        "sensemakingStrategy": "Comparative Model Presentation and 3-2-1 Exit Reflection: Placing the final model beside the Lesson 1 sketch creates a visual representation of the entire unit's conceptual journey — the model comparison is itself an argument about how understanding has changed. The gallery walk allows peer learning and cross-pollination of ideas. The 3-2-1 reflection is a structured metacognitive task that requires learners to consolidate knowledge (3 things understood), apply it to the Kenyan context (2 lifestyle changes), and identify remaining questions (1 wonder), closing the inquiry loop while acknowledging that science continues beyond the classroom.",
        "formativeAssessment": "During the 5-minute final annotation period, teacher checks that all four required elements are present in each group's model. The 90-second presentations are assessed on: (1) Does the learner correctly name coronary arteries and explain their function? (2) Does the learner trace the causal chain from blocked coronary artery → reduced cardiac output → systemic hypoxia → cyanosis of lips? (3) Does the learner connect at least one Kenyan lifestyle factor to atherosclerosis by mechanism (not just by name)? The 3-2-1 exit reflections are collected and reviewed after class: look for whether 'two lifestyle changes' are mechanistically grounded (e.g., 'reduce saturated fat from nyama choma because saturated fat contributes to fatty deposits in artery walls, narrowing them over time') or superficial ('eat less fat'). These reflections serve as the summative formative assessment for the entire unit and inform teacher planning for revision before the next assessment."
