    "teacherReflection": "1. Did learners' Final Explanation responses demonstrate integration of knowledge across all eight lessons — specifically connecting coronary artery structure, cardiac output, systemic circulation, blood composition (haemoglobin), and disease risk factors — or were explanations fragmented and limited to one or two lessons? Which sub-questions (blue lips, faster heartbeat, whole-body effects) remained most difficult, and what might I do differently in earlier lessons to scaffold these connections?\n2. How effectively did the case-study approach (three Kenyan patients) help learners distinguish between atherosclerosis, hypertension, and anaemia as distinct conditions with distinct mechanisms? Were learners able to explain mechanisms or only name diseases?\n3. During the DQB closure ceremony, which questions still had fewer than half the class claiming full understanding? What does this tell me about persistent gaps in the unit, and how should I address these in revision or in the next related unit (Gaseous Exchange and Respiration)?\n4. Comparing the Lesson 1 initial models with the final annotated models — what was the most common conceptual shift I observed across the class? Were there any common persistent misconceptions visible in the final models (e.g., learners still drawing the heart as a single-chamber pump, or failing to show coronary arteries as separate from the systemic circulation)?\n5. Did the lesson timing allow sufficient depth in the Final Explanation task (Explain Phase), which is the most cognitively demanding activity? If learners were rushed, which earlier phase could be shortened in future iterations — and how would I preserve the integrity of the sensemaking in that phase?",
