      "title": "SECTION 1: THE NEED FOR A TRANSPORT SYSTEM AND WHY EVERY CELL WAS AT RISK",
      "prompt": "Explain why the Kericho farmer's body could not survive on diffusion alone. Why do large multicellular organisms like humans need a specialised circulatory system, and how does this mean that a problem in one vessel can threaten every cell in the body? In your answer, refer to the relationship between cell needs, body size, and the role of blood as a transport medium.",
      "exemplar": "The Kericho farmer, like all humans, is a large multicellular organism whose body is made up of trillions of cells. These cells are located far from the external environment and cannot directly exchange oxygen, glucose, and waste products with their surroundings by diffusion alone. Diffusion is effective only over very short distances, typically a few micrometres, because the rate at which molecules move decreases rapidly as distance increases. A cell located in the farmer's leg muscles or liver is far too distant from the lungs or the intestines for diffusion to supply its needs fast enough to sustain life. This is why a specialised circulatory system is essential in large animals.\n\nBlood acts as the transport medium that bridges this gap. It carries dissolved oxygen from the lungs, absorbed glucose from the small intestine after the farmer eats ugali or githeri, hormones from endocrine glands, and removes carbon dioxide and urea as waste products. Because every single cell in the body depends on this continuous supply, any interruption to blood flow — even in one vessel — can deprive entire tissues of oxygen and nutrients. When the farmer's coronary artery became over 70 percent blocked, the heart muscle cells themselves were starved of oxygen, impairing the pump that drives circulation everywhere. This is why a localised blockage in the heart caused effects throughout the whole body, from his bluish lips to his weakened muscles."
