      "exemplar": "The human heart is a muscular organ located slightly to the left in the chest cavity. It is divided into four chambers: the right atrium, right ventricle, left atrium, and left ventricle. The left ventricle has a much thicker muscular wall because it must generate enough pressure to pump oxygenated blood to every part of the body, including the farmer's working leg muscles as he walks uphill from his maize field in Kericho. Valves, including the bicuspid, tricuspid, and semilunar valves, ensure that blood flows in one direction only and prevent backflow during each heartbeat.\n\nThe cardiac cycle consists of diastole, when the heart muscle relaxes and chambers fill with blood, and systole, when the ventricles contract and push blood into the arteries. When the farmer was carrying a heavy sack uphill, his muscles demanded more oxygen and glucose. The nervous system and hormones such as adrenaline increased his heart rate so that more blood could be delivered per minute, a normal physiological response. However, his coronary arteries — the vessels that branch from the aorta and supply the heart muscle itself with oxygen and nutrients — were severely narrowed by fatty deposits called atherosclerotic plaques. When the heart muscle was working harder, it needed even more oxygen, but the blocked coronary artery could not deliver enough. Sections of the cardiac muscle became ischaemic, meaning deprived of oxygen, and began to malfunction. This disrupted the electrical signals that coordinate the heartbeat, causing the rapid and irregular pulse the community health volunteer detected, a condition known as arrhythmia."
