      "exemplar": "Arteries carry blood away from the heart under high pressure. They have thick, muscular, and elastic walls that can withstand and smooth out the surge of blood during each heartbeat. Veins carry blood back toward the heart under low pressure and have thinner walls and valves to prevent backflow. Capillaries are microscopic vessels with walls only one cell thick, allowing efficient exchange of oxygen, glucose, carbon dioxide, and other substances between the blood and surrounding tissues. This network connects to every organ in the farmer's body, from his brain to his fingertips.\n\nIn the pulmonary circuit, deoxygenated blood is pumped from the right ventricle through the pulmonary artery to the lungs, where it picks up oxygen and releases carbon dioxide. The now oxygenated blood returns to the left atrium via the pulmonary veins. In the systemic circuit, this oxygenated blood is pumped by the left ventricle through the aorta to all body tissues, including the lips, skin, and muscles. At the capillaries, oxygen is released to cells and carbon dioxide is collected, and the deoxygenated blood returns to the right atrium through the venae cavae.\n\nThe farmer's lips turned bluish, a condition called cyanosis, because his damaged heart was no longer pumping blood effectively. The left ventricle, starved of oxygen through the blocked coronary artery, could not contract with sufficient force. This meant that oxygenated blood was not being delivered adequately to peripheral tissues such as the lips and extremities. The blood in the small vessels near the skin surface remained low in oxygen, giving the characteristic bluish tint. In Kenyan hospitals, nurses are trained to check for cyanosis as a quick visual indicator of poor oxygenation, and this is exactly what bystanders observed in the farmer before he even reached Kericho County Referral Hospital."
