      "exemplar": "Blood is composed of four main components. Plasma is the liquid matrix, making up about 55 percent of blood volume, and it carries dissolved substances including glucose from digested food, hormones, antibodies, urea for excretion, and carbon dioxide. Red blood cells, or erythrocytes, are biconcave and lack a nucleus, maximising space for haemoglobin, the iron-containing protein that binds oxygen in the lungs and releases it to respiring tissues. White blood cells, or leucocytes, defend the body against pathogens and are part of the immune system. Platelets are cell fragments that are essential for blood clotting, which is what seals a wound and prevents excessive blood loss during surgery.\n\nBlood group compatibility is critical when the farmer needs a transfusion. The ABO blood group system classifies blood into groups A, B, AB, and O based on the antigens present on red blood cell surfaces and the antibodies present in the plasma. If the farmer has blood group A and is given group B blood, his plasma contains anti-B antibodies that will attack the donated red blood cells, causing agglutination and haemolysis. This immune reaction can cause kidney failure, shock, and even death, making incompatible transfusion extremely dangerous.\n\nThe Kenya National Blood Transfusion Service, known as KNBTS, runs regular blood donation campaigns in schools, churches, and community centres across counties including Kericho, Kisumu, and Nairobi. Donors are always typed and screened before their blood is stored. Understanding blood groups is therefore not just a classroom concept — it is a life-saving practice. If more community members in Kericho donated blood regularly and understood the science behind compatibility, emergency supplies for patients like the farmer would be more readily available."
